rt und zugleich Rawls’ Argumentation hinsichtlich ihrer Tragweite, aber auch ihrer Grenzen erörtert.  aJohn Rawls’s second major work, Political Liberalism (1993), is devoted to the question of how a liberal society can arrive at a consensus regarding questions of justice given its societal pluralism. The essays provide systematic interpretations of the work by internationally renowned researchers and, at the same time, examine the broad scope of Rawls’s arguments as well as their limitations.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn German.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aJusticevCongresses. 0aLiberalismvCongresses. 0aPolitical stabilityvCongresses. 4aGerechtigkeit. 4aGesellschaft. 4aKommentar. 4aPluralismus. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Political.2bisacsh  aSociety, justice, pluralism, commentary.1 aBrantl, Dirk, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHinsch, Wilfried, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHorn, Christoph, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHöffe, Otfried, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHöffe, Otfried, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKoller, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLarmore, Charles, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMeyer, Lukas H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPinzani, Alessandro, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWerle, Denilson L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aÖzmen, Elif, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus DeG Package 2015 Part 1z978311076251808iTitle is part of eBook packag